 GENERAL COMMENTS                                                 4625 1451
                                                                  4625 1451
    This evaluation is based primarily on a theoretical analysis  4625 1451
 between neutron energies of 1 keV and 30 MeV that is optimized   4625 1451
 to the somewhat limited available experimental data.  Below 1    4625 1451
 keV, the calculations are matched to resonance parameter         4625 1451
 evaluations, where possible, and are adjusted for consistency    4625 1451
 with thermal cross sections and resonance integrals.  The only   4625 1451
 ENDF/B-VI data that are retained are the resonance parameter     4625 1451
 evaluation for Pd105 and parts of the data at the very lowest    4625 1451
 energies for some of the other isotopes.                         4625 1451
    The theoretical calculations utilize Hauser-Feshbach          4625 1451
 statistical theory with corrections for width fluctuations,      4625 1451
 preequilibrium and direct reaction processes.  Coupled-channel   4625 1451
 optical model calculations are used to obtain particle           4625 1451
 transmission coefficients for the Hauser-Feshbach calculations   4625 1451
 for the even isotopes, as well as for the elastic and direct     4625 1451
 inelastic neutron cross sections and angular distributions.  The 4625 1451
 same potential without deformation is used for Pd105.            4625 1451
    Cross sections and spectra for individual reactions are       4625 1451
 included for exiting neutron, proton, deuteron, alpha, and       4625 1451
 gamma-ray reactions that exceed a cross section of approximately 4625 1451
 1 mb at any energy.  Multiplicities, angular distributions, and  4625 1451
 emission energy spectra are given for gamma rays, particles, and 4625 1451
 recoil nuclei emitted in each reaction, utilizing File 6 of the  4625 1451
 ENDF/B-6 format [Ro91].  Energy-angle-correlated spectra are     4625 1451
 given for all outgoing particles and photons, and residual       4625 1451
 nuclei energy distributions are included.                        4625 1451
                                                                  4625 1451
 THEORY                                                           4625 1451
                                                                  4625 1451
   HAUSER-FESHBACH STATISTICAL THEORY CALCULATIONS.  The GNASH    4625 1451
 code [Yo92] was used for all Hauser-Feshbach statistical theory  4625 1451
 calculations.  Preequilibrium corrections were performed in the  4625 1451
 course of the GNASH calculations using the exciton model of      4625 1451
 Kalbach [Ka77,Ka85].  Discrete level data from nuclear data      4625 1451
 sheets were matched to continuum level densities using the       4625 1451
 formulation of Gilbert and Cameron [Gi65] and pairing and shell  4625 1451
 parameters from the Cook [Co67] analysis.  Neutron and charged-  4625 1451
 particle transmission coefficients were obtained from the        4625 1451
 optical potentials, as discussed below.  Gamma-ray transmission  4625 1451
 coefficients were calculated using the Kopecky-Uhl model [Ko90]. 4625 1451
   Calculations were performed for all significant reactions      4625 1451
 producing neutrons, protons, deuterons, alpha particles, and     4625 1451
 gamma rays for incident neutrons between 1.0E-11 and 30 MeV.  At 4625 1451
 the highest energies, approximately 13 compound nuclei were      4625 1451
 included, leading to ~71 reaction paths.                         4625 1451
   The angular distribution systematics by Kalbach [Ka88] were    4625 1451
 used to describe the angular distributions for all continuum     4625 1451
 particles.                                                       4625 1451
                                                                  4625 1451
   OPTICAL MODEL POTENTIALS.  For incident and exiting neutrons,  4625 1451
 a phenomenological optical model potential by Arthur and Young   4625 1451
 [Ar80], based on an analysis of n + Fe and p + Fe reactions, was 4625 1451
 utilized for all isotope.  This potential was developed by       4625 1451
 analyzing proton reaction cross section data and neutron total,  4625 1451
 scattering, and reaction data in the Fe region.  Other           4625 1451
 potentials [e.g., Ya86, Ch89] were investigated but the Arthur   4625 1451
 potential was found to give the best results.  The Arthur        4625 1451
 potential was used (with Wd reduced by 20%) in a 2-phonon        4625 1451
 vibrational model calculation with the ECIS coupled-channel code 4625 1451
 [Ra72].  The 0+ ground state, the 2+ first excited state, the    4625 1451
 0+,2+,4+ cluster of 2-phonon states, and the lowest 3- octupole  4625 1451
 state (near Ex = 2 MeV) were included in the coupled-channel     4625 1451
 calculations for all the even isotopes.                          4625 1451
    For Pd105, spherical optical model calculations were used     4625 1451
 with the Arthur potential to obtain transmission coefficients,   4625 1451
 and corrections for direct reactions were made as described      4625 1451
 below.  The spherical optical model calculations for Pd105, as   4625 1451
 well as for the charged particle reactions, were performed with  4625 1451
 the SCAT2 optical model code [Be92].  The Beccetti-Greenlees     4625 1451
 potential [Be71] was used for protons, the Perey and Perey       4625 1451
 [Pe63] potential was utilized for deuterons, and the potential   4625 1451
 of MacFadden [Mc66] was used for alpha particles.                4625 1451
                                                                  4625 1451
   DIRECT REACTIONS:  Energy-dependent cross sections of          4625 1451
 inelastic neutrons from Pd(n,n') direct reactions were obtained  4625 1451
 for the even isotopes directly from the ECIS 2-phonon            4625 1451
 vibrational model calculations.  Deformation parameters were     4625 1451
 obtained from the Nuclear Data Sheets, adjusted on the basis of  4625 1451
 fitting 13-MeV proton (n,n) and (n,n') data on Pd108 [Ro66] with 4625 1451
 the Arthur potential.  For the odd isotope, the coupled-channel  4625 1451
 calculation of the lowest 2+ level in Pd106 was simply           4625 1451
 distributed among the lowest four excited states of Pd105.       4625 1451
