    Additionally, (n,gamma) cross sections (multiplicities)       4625 1451
 included in MF=12 and energy distributions in MF=15 are taken    4625 1451
 from the GNASH calculations.  In addition to the usual Hauser-   4625 1451
 Feshbach cross section component obtained using the Kopecky-Uhl  4625 1451
 gamma-ray strength function, a semidirect component is included  4625 1451
 in GNASH that enhances the cross section and hardens the         4625 1451
 spectrum near En = 12-14 MeV.                                    4625 1451
    Discrete (n,n') cross sections and angular distributions were 4625 1451
 calculated using a combination of the GNASH and COMNUC [Du70]    4625 1451
 codes for compound nucleus reactions and using ECIS for direct   4625 1451
 reactions.  Preequilibrium components were included in the       4625 1451
 (n,n') reactions at higher energies to estimate direct effects   4625 1451
 (in an average manner) for discrete states not included in the   4625 1451
 ECIS calculations.  Cross sections for a total of 24 excited     4625 1451
 states are included for all the Pd isotopes except Pd102, for    4625 1451
 which 19 states are included.  The elastic angular distributions 4625 1451
 are included in in MF =4;  the (n,n') angular distributions and  4625 1451
 (n,n'gamma) multiplicities are included in MF=6.                 4625 1451
    Cross sections (MF=3) for approximately 20 discrete states    4625 1451
 are usually included for charged-particle reactions, although in 4625 1451
 some cases the structure of the residual nuclei is not known     4625 1451
 well enough for that many states.  Again, multiplicities for     4625 1451
 (n,x gamma) reactions are included in MF=6.                      4625 1451
    Kalbach systematics (Ka88) are used to specify all continuum  4625 1451
 particle angular distributions in MF=6.  All continuum photon    4625 1451
 angular distributions are assumed isotropic.  Residual nucleus   4625 1451
 recoil energy spectra are included in MF=6 for all reactions.    4625 1451
                                                                  4625 1451
   USE OF EXPERIMENTAL DATA.  The available experimental data for 4625 1451
 Pd and Pd isotopes is somewhat limited.  Data that were useful   4625 1451
 for the evaluation are measurements of the neutron total cross   4625 1451
 section for natural Pd; measurements of (n,gamma) cross sections 4625 1451
 for Pd104, Pd105, Pd106, Pd108, and Pd110, generally from a few  4625 1451
 keV to several hundred keV or higher; recent [Me95] measurments  4625 1451
 of (n,n'gamma) cross sections up to about 3 MeV for Pd104,       4625 1451
 Pd105, Pd106, Pd108, and Pd110; and a few isolated measurements  4625 1451
 near 14 MeV of (n,2n) or (n,x) reactions leading to radioactive  4625 1451
 products.                                                        4625 1451
    The only adjustments made to the calculated cross sections on 4625 1451
 the basis of the experimental data were as follows:              4625 1451
   1. The total cross sections calculated for the individual      4625 1451
 isotopes with the optical model were multiplied by correction    4625 1451
 factors required to bring the combined natural element cross     4625 1451
 section into agreement with the experimental data.  The          4625 1451
 correction factors were below 3.6% at neutron energies above 1   4625 1451
 MeV but were as large as 20% below 1 MeV.                        4625 1451
   2.  The (n,n') cross sections to the first excited states of   4625 1451
 Pd108 and Pd110 were decreased by about 15% near En = 1 MeV.     4625 1451
 Additionally, corrections were made to the structure data for    4625 1451
 one level in both Pd105 and Pd108.                               4625 1451
   3.  The radiative capture cross sections were used to fine     4625 1451
 tune the normalization of the gamma-ray strength function        4625 1451
 calculations.  The final normalization that was determined was   4625 1451
 near the middle of the range of adjustment that we have          4625 1451
 established from systematics.                                    4625 1451
